  <h2>What is Artificial Intelligence?</h2>
  <p>
    <strong>Artificial Intelligence (AI)</strong> is the ability of computers to perform tasks that normally require human thinking — like recognizing faces, understanding speech, or making decisions.
  </p>

  <h2>How Does AI Learn?</h2>
  <p>
    AI systems learn by looking at <em>lots and lots of examples</em>. This is called <strong>Machine Learning</strong>. For example:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Show an AI 1,000 photos of cats → it learns what a cat looks like.</li>
    <li>Give an AI millions of sentences → it learns to understand and write language.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>AI You've Already Used!</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>🎵 <strong>Spotify / YouTube</strong> — Recommends songs and videos you might like.</li>
    <li>🗣️ <strong>Siri / Alexa / Google Assistant</strong> — Understand and answer your questions.</li>
    <li>📸 <strong>Face Unlock on your phone</strong> — Recognizes your face!</li>
    <li>🚗 <strong>Self-driving cars</strong> — AI that drives a car safely.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Is AI Dangerous?</h2>
  <p>
    AI is a powerful tool — like a hammer or a knife. Used well, it helps doctors, scientists, and teachers. The important thing is that <em>humans</em> stay in charge and use AI responsibly!
  </p>

  <blockquote>
    AI doesn't actually "think" like a human — it finds patterns in data. But it can do this so well that it seems almost magical!
  </blockquote>

